  "answer": "The critic misreads the standard. The target does name a specific causal mechanism: the institutional process by which simultaneous diffusion of iron metallurgy and naval warfare technologies enabled non-palace actors (marauders, mercenaries, private traders) to bypass or overwhelm palace monopolies on force and long-distance exchange. This is a concrete process involving identifiable actors, incentives (autonomous wealth and military capability outside palace control), and institutional change (collapse of palace redistribution systems). The reference to network models and phase transitions is not the mechanism itself but an explanatory framework that formalizes how this institutional-technological process produced system-wide collapse from local actions—precisely the kind of causal articulation the standard demands. The forbidden case concerning iron weapon distribution is directly engaged by the mechanism: the target explicitly posits that iron technology diffused to non-palace actors, enabling them to challenge palace military monopolies. If iron weapons were instead dominant in Sea Peoples assemblages and absent from Egyptian military equipment, this would contradict the mechanism’s claim that iron diffusion empowered peripheral groups against palace armies, thereby falsifying the target. The critic’s assertion that the target fails to incorporate this evidence into its logic is incorrect; the mechanism’s entire causal chain depends on iron and naval technologies reaching non-palace actors, and the forbidden case tests precisely that empirical implication."
